content.description:
Start about 12 feet left of Light Touch and just left of a nolina. This nolina is about eight feet right of a pine tree.

Do the first (crux) move of Three Dorks on Dope, then go up and left to a stance (this route's crux). Climb the sculpted face left of the upper crack of Three Dorks on Dope to the top.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack. Large cams and cordelette needed to rig a TR.
content.location: Start about 12 feet left of Light Touch and just left of a nolina. This nolina is about eight feet right of a pine tree.

content.description:
Start just left of Summit or Plummet at the next set of parallel cracks.

Climb up along the parallel cracks to the top.
content.protection: TCUs and small cams for the route, medium cams and cordelette to TR.
content.location: Start just left of Summit or Plummet at the next set of parallel cracks.

content.description:
Start just right of Laeger Domain at a large pod and a short right facing corner.

Climb the right facing corner then past two big huecos to a crack and the top.

Patty wrote the JT hiking guidebook "On Foot in Joshua Tree."
content.protection:
Carry a standard JT rack.

To TR, you'll likely want to wrap a large boulder. You'll need an anchor rope to set up a TR.
content.location: Start just right of Laeger Domain at a large pod and below a short right facing corner.

climbs.name: Three Dorks on Dope
climbs.fa: Dave Mayville, Brandt Allen, Tom Burke 1999

content.description:
Start about 12 feet left of Light Touch and just left of a nolina. This nolina is about eight feet right of a pine tree.

Make a bouldery move off the ground (crux), then climb the vertical crack that is formed by a series of vertical pockets.
content.protection: Cams, TCUs and Tricams will fit in the pockets. Large cams and cordelettes needed to rig a TR.
content.location: Start about 12 feet left of Light Touch and just left of a nolina. This nolina is about eight feet right of a pine tree.

content.description:
On the side of Summit or Plummet Rock that faces the Swidgeteria (the west face of SoP Rock), is a short, steep face. This route climbs the leftmost crack system on this face. The climb is roughly 35 feet down and right of Gailurrera.

Make bouldery moves up into a stance below a short off-width. Thrutch up the wide crack (large cam) to the top.

This route gets afternoon sun.
content.protection: Carry a large cam (purple Camalot or bigger). You'll need slings and/or a cordelette to rig a TR.
content.location: On the side of Summit or Plummet Rock that faces the Swidgeteria, is a short, steep face. This route climbs the leftmost crack system on this face. The climb is roughly 35 feet down and right of Gailurrera.

content.description:
Start about 10 feet down and left of the pine tree and Two Dopes on Pork at a thin vertical crack.

Climb up a short left facing flake then climb the thin vertical crack to the top.
content.protection: Thin gear for the crack, medium cams and cordelette for an anchor.
content.location: Start about 10 feet down and left of the pine tree and Two Dopes on Pork at a thin vertical crack.

content.description:
Start just right of the pod and short right facing corner that is the line of Three Friends and a Baby.

Climb the face just right of the large pod along some plates (5.8 R) to reach an obvious, grainy, hand crack, which is followed to the summit.
content.protection:
Carry a standard JT rack with extra gold and blue Camalots.

To TR, you'll likely want to wrap a large boulder. You'll need an anchor rope to set up a TR.
content.location: Start just right of the pod and short right facing corner that is the line of Three Friends and a Baby.

content.description:
Start in the same spot as Split Shift, just right of a pod and short right facing corner.

Climb up and right on face holds (5.8 PG13) to gain the left end of a large ledge/ramp. Climb the steep, grainy, hand and fist crack directly above (crux).

This crack is just around the nose from the Split Shift crack.
content.protection: In addition to a standard JT rack, carry extra gold and blue Camalots.
content.location: Start in the same spot as Split Shift, just right of a pod and short right facing corner.

content.description:
Start about 10 feet right of Cumbre at a small boulder that leans against the middle of the face.

Climb up and slightly right from the boulder to the top. The holds aren't as good as you might first assume.
content.protection: Medium to large cams and a cordelette needed to rig a TR.
content.location: Start about 10 feet right of Cumbre at a small boulder that leans against the middle of the face.

content.description:
Start about 20 feet right of Misplaced Priorities near a nolia that is at the base of a corner.

Climb a few feet up the corner, then undercling left on a loose flake to reach a crack/flake. Use the crack/flake to pull past a ceiling (crux). Climb the face above to the summit.
content.protection: A couple cams and slings around flakes make up the anchor. You'll also need slings or a cordelette to rig a TR.
content.location:
Start about 20 feet right of Misplaced Priorities near a nolia that is at the base of a corner. This route basically climbs the right side of the face along an obvious flake system.

Descend as for Misplaced Priorities.

content.description:
Start eight feet right of Sommet at an obvious, varnished, right facing corner.

Climb the corner to the top.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack. Anchor rope needed to rig a TR.
content.location: Start eight feet right of Sommet at an obvious, varnished, right facing corner.

content.description:
Begin a couple feet right of Misplaced Modifiers below a corner that leads to a ceiling.

Climb up to a ledge in the corner, then up the loose corner to the ceiling. Move up and right past the ceiling to a stance, then up the short, loose finger crack to the top.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack. You'll need slings and an anchor rope or cordelette to set up a TR.
content.location:
Begin a couple feet right of Misplaced Modifiers below a corner that leads to a ceiling.

To descend, climb down and left to a ledge (above the initial crack on Misplaced Modifiers). Scramble away from the road through a notch and then down to the base of Cumbre. Walk around west to get back to the base of the route.

content.description:
Start roughly 15 feet right of the base of the ramp that accesses Dangling Participles below an obvious vertical crack.

Jam up the crack to a ledge (optional belay here), then climb another clean crack on the left to the top of the formation.
content.protection: Hand and fist sized cams are needed.
content.location:
Start roughly 15 feet right of the base of the ramp that accesses Dangling Participles below an obvious vertical crack.

Scramble down the back (away from the road) of the formation.

content.description:
Start just left of Kodas Silence at the next vertical seam with two bolts.

Climb up the seam past two bolts (crux), then up an easier vertical crack to the summit.
content.protection: Two bolts, standard JT rack.
content.location: Start just left of Kodas Silence at the next vertical seam with two bolts.

climbs.name: Laeger Domain
climbs.fa: Herb Laeger, Rich Perch, Vaino Kodas, and Bob Yoho, Nov. 1987

content.description: steep face and thin crack, a fun climb
content.protection: one bolt plus mostly thin gear
content.location: on the steep, continuous part of the east face

climbs.name: Kodas Silence
climbs.fa: Vaino Kodas, Rich Perch, Herb Laeger & Bob Yoho, November 1987

content.description: This climbs the center crack and face.
content.protection: Pro to 1", two bolts.

content.description:
Start in the same spot as Thrash or Crash, on the back (west) side of Summit or Plummet Rock.

Reach a horizontal crack and hand traverse right about eight feet. Pull up into a short hand crack, which is followed to the top.

This route gets afternoon sun.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT Rack. You'll need larger cams and an anchor rope to set up a TR.
content.location: Start in the same spot as Thrash or Crash, on the back (west) side of Summit or Plummet Rock.

content.description:
Start about 25 feet right (toward Hidden Valley CG) of the starts of Thrash or Crash and Grip or Slip below the next vertical crack system. This crack is next to a large boulder.

Either climb the crack directly or start by stemming off the boulder. Follow the crack past a wider section to the top.

The climb gets sun in the afternoon.
content.protection:
Carry a standard JT rack.

Large cams and anchor rope needed to set up a TR.
content.location: Start about 25 feet right (toward Hidden Valley CG) of the starts of Thrash or Crash and Grip or Slip below the next vertical crack system. This crack is next to a large boulder.

content.description:
Start about 10 feet right and around the corner from Samiti at an obvious varnished crack.

Climb the hand and fist crack to a ledge under an overhang. Step left around the overhang and up to the top.
content.protection: Carry several hand and fist sized pieces.
content.location: Start about 10 feet right and around the corner from Samiti at an obvious varnished crack.

content.description:
Start about ten feet right of Gipfel at a vertical crack in a small corridor made up of two large boulders.

Climb the crack to a niche, then go up and right along a flake and varnished patches to the top.

Route gets afternoon sun.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack. Scramble off.
content.location: Start about ten feet right of Gipfel at a vertical crack in a small corridor made up of two large boulders.

content.description:
Start about 50 feet right of Split Shift/Split Infinitive at the right end of a ramp. Scramble up and left on the ramp to the far left end and set up a belay behind a big block (Variation 1).

Climb the obvious, right facing corner that is right of the Split Infinitive crack and just left of the big block to the top. A bit loose and a bit grainy.

Variation 1: For a more direct route, climb the first 20 feet of Split Infinitive to gain the left end of the ledge/ramp (5.8 PG13).
content.protection:
Carry a standard JT rack and a couple over the shoulder slings.

You'll probably want to wrap a boulder for an anchor and will need an anchor rope to set up a TR.
content.location: Start about 50 feet right of Split Shift/Split Infinitive at the right end of a ramp. Scramble up and left on the ramp to the far left end and set up a belay behind a big block (V1).

content.description:
This is the leftmost of the routes on the west face of Summit or Plummet Rock. Start at the left edge of the face by some boulders.

Climb up and right along a gritty crack/flake to it's top then up a short vertical crack to the top.
content.protection:
One hand-sized cam at the start and a couple small TCUs or nuts for up higher.

Medium to large cams and cordelette needed to rig a TR.
content.location: This is the leftmost of the routes on the west face of Summit or Plummet Rock. Start at the left edge of the face by some boulders.
